Dashboards & Reporting.description: Provides tools for creating, managing, and sharing visual representations of data through dashboards, notebooks, and graph snapshots. This enables stakeholders to monitor key metrics and build comprehensive reports.

Defines the `WidgetNumberFormat` struct, which specifies number format options like unit and unit scale for widgets in the Datadog API.
This file defines the `WidgetMessageDisplay` enumeration, which specifies the display modes for messages or log lines within a Datadog widget, such as 'inline' or 'expanded' in different sizes.

This file defines the `WidgetGroupSort` struct and its associated methods, used to specify how to sort widgets within a group in the Datadog API client for Go. It includes constructors, field accessors, and JSON marshalling/unmarshalling logic.

This file defines the `WidgetTickEdge` enum, which specifies how text should be aligned on a widget (e.g., top, bottom, left, right). It includes methods for validation and JSON unmarshalling for this enum.

This file defines the `WidgetSummaryType` enum, specifying valid summary types ('monitors', 'groups', 'combined') for a widget in the Datadog API client. It includes methods for validation, serialization, and retrieval of allowed enum values.

Defines the `WidgetSort` enumeration, representing possible sorting methods (ascending or descending) for widgets, along with utility methods for its handling and validation.

Defines the `WidgetTime` struct, a union type (`oneOf`) that encapsulates different representations of time settings for a widget, including legacy live spans, new live spans, and new fixed spans. It handles the serialization and deserialization of these various time configurations.

This file defines the `ActionQueryShowToastOnError` type, a union type that can be either a boolean or a string, used to specify whether to display a toast message when a query returns an error. It includes methods for JSON marshaling and unmarshaling this type.

Platform & Integration Management.description: Manages connections to third-party services and cloud providers like AWS, Azure, GCP, Slack, and PagerDuty. This enables seamless data ingestion and action execution across the entire platform.

files.description: This file demonstrates how to create a new AWS integration account in Datadog using the `CreateAWSAccount` API endpoint from the Go client library. It sets up an AWS account with specific configuration details, including account ID, region rules, and tag filters.
This file is an example Go program that demonstrates how to list AWS tag filters associated with a specific AWS account using the Datadog API client.
This file demonstrates how to delete an Amazon EventBridge source integration using the Datadog API client for Go.
This file demonstrates how to delete a specific AWS tag filtering entry using the Datadog API client for Go, targeting a given AWS account ID and namespace.
This file is a Go example demonstrating how to list all Amazon EventBridge sources using the Datadog API client. It calls the `ListAWSEventBridgeSources` endpoint and prints the response.

This Go program demonstrates how to delete an existing AWS integration using the Datadog API client. It constructs a request with an AWS account ID and role name, then calls the DeleteAWSAccount API endpoint.
This Go example lists all AWS integrations configured within Datadog using the Datadog API client. It retrieves and prints the details of the AWS accounts.

This file demonstrates how to update an existing AWS integration in Datadog using the Go API client. It configures various settings for an AWS account and then calls the `UpdateAWSAccount` API endpoint.
This Go example demonstrates how to create an AWS tag filter using the Datadog API client. It sets a tag filter for an AWS account in the ELB namespace with a tag string of 'prod*'.
This file demonstrates how to create a new AWS external ID and configure an AWS integration using the Datadog API client for Go.

This file provides a Go example for creating an AWS EventBridge source within Datadog using the Datadog API client. It configures a new EventBridge source with specified account and region details and then calls the API to create it.
This file is an example Go program that demonstrates how to list available AWS namespaces using the Datadog API client. It calls the `ListAvailableAWSNamespaces` API and prints the response.
This Go example demonstrates how to use the Datadog API client to update an existing action connection, specifically modifying an AWS integration's role and account ID.
This file demonstrates how to create a new AWS integration account in Datadog using the Datadog API client for Go, including configuration for authentication, logs, metrics, resources, and traces.
This Go example demonstrates how to delete an AWS integration account using the Datadog API client. It fetches the AWS account ID from an environment variable and calls the `DeleteAWSAccount` API.

This Go example creates an AWS EventBridge source with a specified account ID, region, and event generator name using the Datadog API client, optionally creating a new event bus. It then prints the API response or any errors encountered.
This Go example lists available AWS namespaces using the Datadog API client (v2). It retrieves and prints the namespaces to standard output in JSON format.
This Go example retrieves details for a specific AWS integration configured in Datadog using its configuration ID. It demonstrates how to use the Datadog API client to fetch AWS account information.
This file is a Go example demonstrating how to create a new AWS integration account in Datadog using the v2 API, including configuration for metrics, logs, traces, and resources.
This file demonstrates how to list all AWS integration accounts configured in Datadog using the Go API client.
This file demonstrates how to generate a new AWS external ID using the Datadog API client for Go. It calls the `CreateNewAWSExternalID` API endpoint and prints the response.
This file is a Go example demonstrating how to retrieve the standard AWS integration IAM permissions using the Datadog API client.
This file is an example program that demonstrates how to retrieve the AWS IAM permissions object using the Datadog API client for Go.
This Go example demonstrates how to generate a new AWS external ID using the Datadog API client, printing the returned external ID object.
This file demonstrates how to delete an Amazon EventBridge source integration in Datadog using the Go API client.
This file demonstrates how to update an existing AWS integration in Datadog using the Datadog API client for Go, including various configuration settings for metrics, logs, traces, and resources.
This file is a Go example demonstrating how to retrieve the collection of AWS integration IAM permissions using the Datadog API client.
This Go example file demonstrates how to use the Datadog API client to list available AWS namespaces through the AWS integration API.
This file is a Go example demonstrating how to retrieve the AWS IAM permissions resource collection using the Datadog API client.
This program retrieves and prints the standard IAM permissions required for Datadog AWS integration using the Datadog API client.
This Go example retrieves and prints a list of all Amazon EventBridge sources configured in Datadog, utilizing the Datadog API client library.

This file contains integration tests for the Datadog AWS Integration API, covering operations such as creating, updating, deleting, and generating external IDs for AWS accounts, as well as listing available AWS namespaces and error handling.

This directory is intended to store test fixtures specifically for AWS-related functionalities within the Datadog API v1 client for Go. It serves as a placeholder for data or configurations needed to run tests against AWS integrations. Although currently empty, its structure indicates its designated role in supporting API test cases.

This directory stores recorded HTTP request/response "cassettes" for testing purposes. Specifically, these cassettes are used to simulate and verify error handling when deleting AWS integrations via the Datadog V1 API client. They enable repeatable and isolated testing of error scenarios without actual API calls.

This directory stores recorded HTTP responses, known as cassettes, for tests related to updating AWS integrations within the Datadog API v1. These cassettes specifically capture error scenarios, allowing tests to be run offline and consistently.

This directory stores recorded HTTP interactions (cassettes) for a test suite within the Datadog Go API client. Specifically, it contains the VCR cassettes used to simulate and verify the handling of conflict errors during the creation of AWS integrations via the Datadog API v1.

This directory stores pre-recorded HTTP request/response 'cassettes' specifically for the `TestAWSLogsServicesEnableErrors` test case within the `datadogV1` API tests. These cassettes enable reproducible and isolated testing by replaying network interactions without contacting the actual Datadog API service. It ensures consistent test outcomes when simulating error conditions for AWS Logs service enablement.

This directory stores HTTP interaction cassettes for the `TestAWSIntegrationGenerateExternalIDErrors` test within the `datadogV1` API client tests. These cassettes are crucial for enabling deterministic and isolated offline testing by replaying recorded API responses. They ensure consistent test behavior for the AWS integration's external ID error generation logic.

This directory stores VCR cassettes specifically for tests that simulate and verify error handling during the creation of AWS integrations using Datadog API V1. These cassettes record HTTP interactions, allowing tests to run deterministically without actual network calls, focusing on various error scenarios.

This directory stores pre-recorded HTTP interactions, or 'cassettes', specifically for integration tests related to AWS features within the v1 Datadog API client for Go. These cassettes are used to mock API responses, ensuring consistent and isolated testing of AWS integration scenarios.

This directory is intended to store HTTP request/response cassettes for scenario tests. Specifically, it houses recordings used to validate the Datadog API v2's AWS Logs Integration feature, ensuring reproducible and isolated test execution.

This directory stores HTTP interaction 'cassettes' for integration tests within the Datadog Go API client. Specifically, it contains pre-recorded API responses for version 2 of the API, used to test the AWS Integration features.

CI/CD Visibility.description: Provides insights into the performance and health of continuous integration and delivery pipelines. It includes analytics on test runs, flaky test detection, and pipeline event tracking.

files.description: This Go program demonstrates how to create a Datadog CI Pipelines monitor using the Datadog API client. It defines the monitor's type, query, message, tags, priority, and thresholds, then creates it via an API call.

Synthetic Monitoring.description: Allows for the proactive monitoring of applications and APIs from global locations. Users can simulate user journeys and API requests to ensure availability and performance before users are impacted.

Service Catalog & API Management.description: Provides tools to discover, manage, and govern services and their APIs within a centralized software catalog. This ensures consistency and visibility into the organization's microservices architecture.

files.description: This file demonstrates how to create a new OpenAPI specification in Datadog using the Go client library, by uploading an `openapi-spec.yaml` file.
This file demonstrates how to update an existing OpenAPI specification using the Datadog API client for Go, reading the specification from a local 'openapi-spec.yaml' file.
This file demonstrates how to delete an existing OpenAPI specification from Datadog API Management using the Go client library.
This Go example file demonstrates how to list APIs using the Datadog API client, specifically utilizing the `v2.ListAPIs` endpoint to retrieve and print API details.

This Go example demonstrates how to retrieve the OpenAPI specification for a managed API using the Datadog API client. It fetches an API ID from an environment variable and prints the OpenAPI content to standard output.

This file is an example Go program that lists all Datadog reference tables using the `ListTables` API endpoint and prints the response.

Application Performance Monitoring (APM).description: Offers deep visibility into application performance by analyzing traces and spans. It helps developers troubleshoot latency, errors, and service dependencies across distributed systems.
